messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path: /api/users/logout

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable? No. The logout endpoint is defined only for POST in the routes.

- HEAD: Not acceptable (no HEAD handler defined for this path; only POST is implemented).

- POST: Acceptable ( Logout is implemented as a POST route in routes/userRoutes.js and handled by logoutUser).

- OPTIONS: Not acceptable (no OPTIONS handler defined for this path).

- TRACE: Not acceptable (no TRACE handler defined for this path).

- GET: Not acceptable (no GET handler defined for this path).

- PUT: Not acceptable (no PUT handler defined for this path).

- DELETE: Not acceptable (no DELETE handler defined for this path).

- PATCH: Not acceptable (no PATCH handler defined for this path).

Explanation:
- The server mounts user routes at the /api/users prefix (app.use('/api/users', userRoutes.js)).
- In routes/userRoutes.js, logoutUser is registered as router.post('/logout', logoutUser), which makes the full path /api/users/logout and only the POST method valid for this endpoint.
- The logoutUser controller simply clears the jwt cookie and returns a 200 response; there are no handlers for other HTTP methods on this path, hence only POST is acceptable per the code.
